<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOUR MORTGAGE; HOW TO AVOID PRIVATE MORTGAGE INSURANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DIAN HYMER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 How can I avoid private mortgage insurance? 
</P>
<P>
 Private mortgage insurance (PMI) is required by most conventional lenders when 
the borrower makes a cash down payment of less than 20% of the purchase price. 
</P>
<P>
 PMI protects the lender in the event that the borrower stops making payments 
on the loan. PMI is usually paid for by the borrower. A separate approval 
process is required to get a borrower approved for PMI. 
</P>
<P>
 The cost of PMI varies depending on the PMI company, the amount of the cash 
down payment and the type of the loan. PMI for an adjustable-rate mortgage 
(ARM) will cost more than it will for a fixed-rate loan. The more cash you put 
down, the lower will be the cost of the PMI premium. Usually lenders require 
that the borrower pay the entire first year's PMI premium in advance at 
closing, which can add significantly to your closing costs. 
</P>
<P>
 There are several ways to avoid PMI. One is to ask the seller to carry back a 
second mortgage. Lenders vary on how much they require a seller to carry for 
you to avoid PMI. Some won't require PMI if you put 10% down and the sellers 
carry a second loan for 10% of the purchase price. Other lenders (most Freddie 
Mac and Fannie Mae lenders) require that the seller carry a 15% second if the 
borrower puts 10% down (or the seller can carry a 10% second if the borrower 
puts 15% down). 
</P>
<P>
 If a seller-carry back is not possible, you may be able to find a lender 
who'll loan you a second mortgage, but don't expect to find a competitive 
interest rate on such a loan. 
</P>
<P>
 Another option is to ask your parents give you money to apply toward your down 
payment. Or, your employer, or a relative, may be willing to make you a loan 
(either a loan that's secured against the property or an unsecured, personal 
loan). 
</P>
<P>
 Many portfolio lenders don't require PMI when the borrower puts less than 20% 
down. These lenders self-insure for PMI. Their loans usually have a higher 
interest rate than you'll find on a loan that requires separate PMI. 
</P>
<P>
 There are pros and cons to loans with PMI built into the interest rate. On the 
positive side, a separate PMI approval process is not required which saves time 
and eliminates the risk of being turned done by the PMI underwriter. And since 
the cost of PMI is built into the interest rate, it's tax deductible. But, when 
the cost of PMI is built into the interest rate, there's no possibility for 
canceling PMI in the future. 
</P>
<P>
 First-Time Tip: Most lenders will allow you to cancel PMI under certain 
conditions. Some lenders require the borrower to have paid on the loan for 2 to 
5 years before they'll agree to cancel PMI. Others have no time requirement, 
but they require that the LTV (loan-to-value ratio) be 80% or less. In this 
case, an appraisal is required to substantiate the current value of the 
property. Lenders also require a good mortgage payment history (that is, no 
late payments) before they'll agree to drop PMI. Find out before you close your 
home purchase what the lender will require for you to cancel PMI. 
</P>
<P>
 When you think you meet those conditions, contact the loan servicing 
department and find out how to make a formal request to drop PMI. Don't contact 
the PMI company. The decision to cancel PMI is made by the lender, not by the 
PMI company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
